      "content": "Of course, I'd be happy to help with your paper. One key marker of the evolution from primitive to modern societies is the development of complex social hierarchies. In primitive societies, social structures are often based on kinship and tribal affiliations, whereas modern societies have more diverse and intricate systems, including class, caste, and institutional roles. Another significant difference is the role of technology; primitive societies rely on rudimentary tools, while modern societies are characterized by advanced technology and infrastructure. Additionally, modern societies tend to have more formalized and codified legal systems, contrasting with the informal and often customary laws of primitive societies. Lastly, the concept of individual rights and personal freedoms is more pronounced in modern societies compared to the collective focus of primitive communities.",
